<font color="blue">"Yes, I follow Tunare... so what? You gonna judge me by my god, and not the person?"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uanklesdirtyfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ankles Dirtyfoot</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mudslingin' Admin</span><br>  Posts: 224<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/01 3:39:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm43.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=21.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Where to go, what to do...</span><hr size=1> If you enjoy the atmosphere of the lake, stay there. I don't know what the population of players is like right now, but I imagine it's not packed (yet). There are plenty of good spots to pull to, and if you have a chanter to deal with adds in sticky situations - all the better. Of course, any caster capable of rooting will suffice - root parking is a wonderful thing.<br>
<br>
Some places that come to mind as good pull spots:<br>
<br>
Follow the river and turn to the left, go along the wall as far as the ruins. There's a flat area there with virtually no mobs pathing through. You can pull from the wide-open area between the lake and the windmill, as well as from the goblin ruins (be careful pulling from the ruins, there are a few really nasty gobs in there).<br>
<br>
Pillars near the fort - Decent spot for a group or pair. Lots of roaming mobs up the hill, and if you pull down to the water, adds should be non-existent.<br>
<br>
At the sarnak fort - Outside the front door, on the left and right sides are decent spots to pull to. Relatively free of roamers. On the left side (while facing the fort) there are sometimes goblins, tigers and skellies that wander through, but not often enough to make it a problem.<br>
<br>
The back door of the sarnak fort is also a great spot. There's a flat spot of land to the left of the door that makes a great battle area. If you venture inside there's a few rooms that are good to pull to as well. Just explore a bit.<br>
<br>
The &quot;saddle&quot; area of the mountain range has lots of mobs, but it known for its multiple adds. <br>
<br>
The goblin caves are also pretty decent, and single pulls are relatively easy to come by. Just watch what you pull, the level range is pretty diverse.<br>
<br>
If you want to try other spots besides the lake at your level, I have a couple suggestions of my favourite old world zones. <br>
<br>
Highpass - orcs and gnolls. I don't know the exact level range, as I've only fought here for faction with my lizard monk after things had already greened out. Good spot though. Fast pulls, plenty of people to group with, and okay loot.<br>
<br>
Highkeep - a goldmine. You can start here in your teens I'm told, doing the prisoners. Then, around 18ish you can move on to fight the goblin lookouts in the area just at the bottom of the stairs. As you progress, you can kill the warriors, which are much tougher, but do-able in a group of mid-high 20s and give experience through the 30s.<br>
<br>
South Karana - Aviaks, centaurs, dozens of animals, gnolls. <br>
<br>
Splitpaw once you reach your early 20s. Absolutely crazy experience, and nice armor (splitpaw hide = leather with a handful of saves/stats) and weapon (FS) drops.<br>
<br>
Unrest is wonderful.<br>
<br>
Runnyeye can be a lot of fun if you have a good group. Easy to get lost, and the level range of the creatures seems to vary widely in each area but it's an exciting zone with lots of constant action.<br>
<br>
East Karana is another good spot. With tracking you should never be without a mob in reach. Just be wary of the roaming eyes and griffins.<br>
<br>
Hmm, there's plenty more but those are probably my zones of choice for the time being. Hope that helps a bit. Once you hit 22 and get the panic animal spell, soloing will become a dream. Snare, fear, bonk. Rinse, repeat.<br>
